$$ \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i} + 2\mu x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)}{-2\sigma x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)}, \quad i = 1, 2, \dots, n-1 $$

which can be regarded as $n-1$ samples of a standard normal uncertainty distribution. According to the work of Yao and Liu [27], we can obtain parameter estimates by using the sample moments to estimate the population moments. Since there are two unknown parameters in Eq. (6), we equate the first two sample moments to the corresponding first two population moments, i.e.,


$$ \left\{ \begin{aligned} & \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i} + 2\mu x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)}{-2\sigma x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)} = 0 \\ & \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \left( \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i} + 2\mu x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)}{-2\sigma x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)} \right)^2 = 1 \end{aligned} \right. $$

which can be readily solved to yield


$$ \left\{ \begin{aligned} \mu &= -\frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i}}{x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)} \\ \sigma &= \left( \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \left( \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i}}{x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)} - \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \frac{x_{t_{i+1}} - x_{t_i}}{x_{t_i}^2 (t_{i+1} - t_i)} \right) \right)^{\frac{1}{2}} \end{aligned} \right. $$

The theorem is proved. ☐

As stated in Section 2, the concentration of N₂O₅ molecules obeys the form of Eq. (6). Henold and Walmsley [6] has provided a credible collection of data presented in Table 1. By Theorem 4.1, we obtain


$$ \mu = 0.0011, \quad \sigma = 0.0005. $$

Hence the concentration of N₂O₅ molecules at time t satisfies the following uncertain chemical reaction equation,


$$ dX_t = -0.0022X_t^2 dt - 0.0010X_t^2 dC_t, \quad X_0 = 0.31. \qquad (7) $$

The α-path [26] of Eq. (7) satisfies ordinary differential equation


$$ dX_t^\alpha = -0.0022(X_t^\alpha)^2 dt + 0.0010(X_t^\alpha)^2 \Phi^{-1}(\alpha) dt, \quad X_0^\alpha = 0.31 \qquad (8) $$

where $\alpha \in (0, 1)$, and $\Phi^{-1}(\alpha)$ is the inverse standard normal uncertainty distribution, i.e.,


$$ \Phi^{-1}(\alpha) = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{\pi} \ln \frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}. $$

It is easy to check that the analytical solution of Eq. (8) is


$$ X_t^\alpha = \frac{0.31}{0.31[0.0022 - 0.0010\Phi^{-1}(\alpha)]t + 1}. $$

