## 5. Half-life of reaction

Half-life of reaction $\tau_{1/2}$ refers to the time when the concentration of a given reactant is consumed to half of its initial value in a chemical reaction. A short half-life of reaction indicates a high reaction rate.

**Theorem 5.1.** Suppose the molecular concentration $X_t$ at time $t$ follows the uncertain chemical reaction equation


$$dX_t = -2\mu X_t^2 dt - 2\sigma X_t^2 dC_t, \quad X_0 = x_0 \qquad (9)$$

where $\mu$ and $\sigma$ are constants. Then half-life of reaction $\tau_{1/2}$ has an uncertainty distribution


$$\Upsilon(s) = \left( 1 + \exp \left( \frac{\pi}{2\sqrt{3}\sigma} \left( \frac{1}{x_0 s} - 2\mu \right) \right) \right)^{-1}, \quad s > 0.$$

**Proof.** In this case of $s = 0$, the fact that the half-life of reaction must be positive implies


$$\Upsilon(s) = 0.$$

The $\alpha$-path [26] of Eq. (9) satisfies ordinary differential equation


$$dX_t^\alpha = -2\mu(X_t^\alpha)^2 dt + 2\sigma(X_t^\alpha)^2 \Phi^{-1}(\alpha) dt, \quad X_0^\alpha = x_0. \qquad (10)$$

Solving for Eq. (10), we obtain


$$X_t^\alpha = \frac{x_0}{2(\mu - \sigma \Phi^{-1}(\alpha))x_0 t + 1}.$$

In an actual decomposition reaction, the concentration of the reactant decreases as the reaction progresses. Then the initial value is the highest quantity of the reactant that can be observed. However, $X_t^\alpha$ is a strictly increasing function with respect to $t$ for each $\alpha \in (\Phi(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}), 1)$, implying that the concentration of the reactant is bound to exceed the initial value. Thus, $\alpha$ cannot be valued with range $(\Phi(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}), 1)$. As described above, we will just consider the case $\alpha \in (0, \Phi(\frac{\mu}{\sigma}))$. When $s > 0$, using the first hitting time theorem of solution of uncertain differential equation [13], we obtain


$$\begin{aligned} \Upsilon(s) &= \mathcal{M}\{\tau_{1/2} \le s\} \\ &= \sup \left\{ \alpha \mid \inf_{0 \le t \le s} X_t^\alpha \le \frac{x_0}{2} \right\} \\ &= \sup \left\{ \alpha \mid \inf_{0 \le t \le s} \frac{x_0}{2(\mu - \sigma \Phi^{-1}(\alpha))x_0 t + 1} \le \frac{x_0}{2} \right\} \\ &= \sup \left\{ \alpha \mid \frac{x_0}{2(\mu - \sigma \Phi^{-1}(\alpha))x_0 s + 1} \le \frac{x_0}{2} \right\} \\ &= \sup \left\{ \alpha \mid \alpha \le \Phi\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma} - \frac{1}{2\sigma x_0 s}\right) \right\} \\ &= \Phi\left(\frac{\mu}{\sigma} - \frac{1}{2\sigma x_0 s}\right) \\ &= \left(1 + \exp\left(\frac{\pi}{2\sqrt{3}\sigma}\left(\frac{1}{x_0 s} - 2\mu\right)\right)\right)^{-1}. \end{aligned}$$

The theorem is proved. $\square$

