## Appendix A. Paradox of the stochastic chemical kinetics

In the stochastic chemical kinetics, the dynamic behavior of noise is described by Wiener process $W_t$. For the irreversible decomposition of N₂O₅, assume the concentration of N₂O₅ molecules satisfies the stochastic differential equation


$$dX_t = -2\mu X_t^2 dt - 2\sigma X_t^2 dW_t. \qquad (A.1)$$

We may use the estimated values in Section 4 to approximate $μ$ and $σ$ in Eq. (A.1), i.e., $μ = 0.0011$, $σ = 0.0005$. Let $Δt$ be small enough, e.g., taking $Δt = 10^{-4}$. Then from the numerical algorithm,


$$\Pr\{X_{t+Δt} - X_t > 0\} = 49.12\%$$

at each time $t$. This result shows that the concentration of N₂O₅ molecules increases at any given time with a probability 49.12%. However, in the actual decomposition reaction, the concentration of N₂O₅ molecules decreases over time. Thus, the noise is incorrectly described by Wiener process.

